    "reasoning": "1. **State Definition**: The Lemming has two main walking directions (Left, Right) and two vertical states (On Ground, Falling). This results in 4 distinct behavioral states: \n    - `WALK_LEFT_GROUND`: Walking left, on the ground.\n    - `WALK_RIGHT_GROUND`: Walking right, on the ground.\n    - `FALL_LEFT`: Falling, but the last walking direction was left.\n    - `FALL_RIGHT`: Falling, but the last walking direction was right.\n2. **Transitions**:\n    - From `WALK_LEFT_GROUND`: If `ground=0`, move to `FALL_LEFT`. If `bump_right=1`, move to `WALK_RIGHT_GROUND`. If `bump_left=1`, stay in `WALK_LEFT_GROUND` (or if both, stay in `WALK_LEFT_GROUND` is not specified, but usually, left bump while walking left does nothing; however, the spec says 'If it's bumped on the left, it will walk right'. Wait, let's re-read: 'If a Lemming is bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it's bumped on the right, it will walk left. If it's bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.')\n    - Correction on Bump Logic: \n        - If `bump_left` is high: target direction is Right.\n        - If `bump_right` is high: target direction is Left.\n        - If both are high: the spec says 'it will still switch directions'. This is slightly ambiguous. Let's look at the common sense of the game: if you are walking left and hit a wall on the left, you go right. If you hit walls on both sides, you change direction (from Left to Right, or Right to Left). However, if `bump_left` and `bump_right` are both 1, it's a direction switch. Let's assume if `bump_left` is 1, the next direction is Right. If `bump_right` is 1, the next direction is Left. If both are 1, it's a toggle or a specific rule. Re-reading: 'If it's bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.' This implies the direction flips. But usually, in RTL, we define priority. Let's use: if `bump_left && !bump_right` -> Right; if `!bump_left && bump_right` -> Left; if `bump_left && bump_right` -> toggle direction.\n    - Actually, a simpler interpretation of 'switch directions' for both sides: if direction was Left, it becomes Right. If direction was Right, it becomes Left. This is equivalent to `dir_next = ~dir_curr` when both are bumped.\n    - **Ground Logic**: If `ground=0`, the state enters the 'FALL' variants. If `ground=1`, it returns to the 'GROUND' variant with the same direction.\n    - **Reset**: `areset` is asynchronous, positive edge. Reset state is `WALK_LEFT_GROUND`.\n3. **Moore Outputs**:\n    - `walk_left`: 1 if state is `WALK_LEFT_GROUND` or `FALL_LEFT` (Wait, the spec says 'when ground=0, the Lemming will fall and say aaah!'. This means `aaah` is 1 when `ground=0`. The walking outputs should probably be 0 while falling, or do they continue? 'When the ground reappears, the Lemming will resume walking in the same direction'. This implies the walking direction is preserved. Let's check the output requirements. `walk_left` and `walk_right` are the walking states. Usually, in these problems, `walk_left` is 1 if the Lemming is currently walking left. If it's falling, it's not 'walking' on ground, but the direction is preserved. Let's look at the outputs: `walk_left`, `walk_right`, `aaah`. If `aaah` is 1, it is falling. If `aaah` is 0, it is walking. It's impossible to be walking and falling simultaneously. So `walk_left` and `walk_right` should be 0 when `aaah` is 1.\n4. **Refined State Machine**:\n    - States:\n        - `L_G`: Walking Left, Grounded.\n        - `R_G`: Walking Right, Grounded.\n        - `L_F`: Falling, last was Left.\n        - `R_F`: Falling, last was Right.\n    - Transitions:\n        - `L_G`: if `ground=0` -> `L_F`. Else if `bump_right` -> `R_G`. Else if `bump_left` -> `R_G`. Else if `both` -> `R_G` (switch direction).\n        - `R_G`: if `ground=0` -> `R_F`. Else if `bump_left` -> `L_G`. Else if `bump_right` -> `L_G`. Else if `both` -> `L_G`.\n        - `L_F`: if `ground=1` -> `L_G`. (Bumps ignored while falling).\n        - `R_F`: if `ground=1` -> `R_G`. (Bumps ignored while falling).\n    - **Wait**, let's re-read: 'If it's bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it's bumped on the right, it will walk left. If it's bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.' This means: \n        - `bump_left` alone -> Right.\n        - `bump_right` alone -> Left.\n        - `bump_left && bump_right` -> Toggle.\n        - This is exactly: `if (bump_left && !bump_right) dir = Right; else if (!bump_left && bump_right) dir = Left; else if (bump_left && bump_right) dir = ~dir;` \n        - BUT, if the Lemming is walking Left and hits `bump_left`, it should go Right. If it hits `bump_right`, it should go Left. If it hits both, it switches. If it is walking Left and hits `bump_left`, it's already going Left, so it switches to Right. If it hits `bump_right`, it's already going Left, it switches to Right? No, 'If it's bumped on the right, it will walk left'. This is contradictory if the Lemming is already walking left. \n        - Let's simplify: \n            - `bump_left` -> `next_dir = RIGHT`\n            - `bump_right` -> `next_dir = LEFT`\n            - `bump_left && bump_right` -> `next_dir = ~current_dir`\n            - This logic is consistent. If walking Left: `bump_left` -> Right. `bump_right` -> Left. `both` -> Right. If walking Right: `bump_left` -> Right. `bump_right` -> Left. `both` -> Left.\n            - Let's re-read carefully: 'If a Lemming is bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it's bumped on the right, it will walk left. If it's bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.'\n            - If `dir == LEFT`:\n                - `bump_left` -> `RIGHT`\n                - `bump_right` -> `LEFT` (Wait, if it's already walking left and hits a wall on the right, it stays walking left? That makes sense, it's already walking left).\n                - `both` -> `RIGHT` (Switch direction from Left to Right).\n            - If `dir == RIGHT`:\n                - `bump_left` -> `RIGHT` (Already walking right).\n                - `bump_right` -> `LEFT` (Switch direction).\n                - `both` -> `LEFT` (Switch direction from Right to Left).\n            - This logic simplifies to:\n                - `if (bump_left && bump_right) next_dir = ~curr_dir;`\n                - `else if (bump_left) next_dir = RIGHT;`\n                - `else if (bump_right) next_dir = LEFT;`\n                - `else next_dir = curr_dir;`\n5. **Final States**:\n    - `STATE_L_G`, `STATE_R_G`, `STATE_L_F`, `STATE_R_F`.\n    - `aaah` = 1 if state is `L_F` or `R_F`.\n    - `walk_left` = 1 if state is `L_G`.\n    - `walk_right` = 1 if state is `R_G`.\n6. **Advice to avoid syntax errors**:\n    - Always use `always @(*)` for combinational logic.\n    - Use `logic` for all signals.\n    - Ensure the asynchronous reset is in the sensitivity list: `always @(posedge clk or posedge areset)`.\n    - Initialize non-reset signals in an `initial` block to avoid `X` propagation during simulation.\n",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic areset,\n    input  logic bump_left,\n    input  logic bump_right,\n    input  logic ground,\n    output logic walk_left,\n    output logic walk_right,\n    output logic aaah\n);\n\n    // State definitions\n    localparam STATE_L_G = 2'b00; // Walking Left, Grounded\n    localparam STATE_R_G = 2'b01; // Walking Right, Grounded\n    localparam STATE_L_F = 2'b10; // Falling, last was Left\n    localparam STATE_R_F = 2'b11; // Falling, last was Right\n\n    logic [1:0] state;\n    logic [1:0] next_state;\n\n    // Initialize state to prevent X in simulation\n    initial begin\n        state = STATE_L_G;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic with asynchronous reset\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\n        if (areset) begin\n            state <= STATE_L_G;\n        end else begin\n            state <= next_state;\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for next state\n    always @(*) begin\n        next_state = state;\n        case (state)\n            STATE_L_G: begin\n                if (!ground) begin\n                    next_state = STATE_L_F;\n                end else begin\n                    if (bump_left && bump_right) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_R_G; // Switch direction\n                    end else if (bump_left) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_R_G; // Bump left -> walk right\n                    end else if (bump_right) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_L_G; // Bump right -> walk left (already is)\n                    end else begin\n                        next_state = STATE_L_G;\n                    end\n                end\n            end\n            STATE_R_G: begin\n                if (!ground) begin\n                    next_state = STATE_R_F;\n                end else begin\n                    if (bump_left && bump_right) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_L_G; // Switch direction\n                    end else if (bump_left) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_R_G; // Bump left -> walk right (already is)\n                    end else if (bump_right) begin\n                        next_state = STATE_L_G; // Bump right -> walk left\n                    end else begin\n                        next_state = STATE_R_G;\n                    end\n                end\n            end\n            STATE_L_F: begin\n                if (ground) begin\n                    next_state = STATE_L_G;\n                end else begin\n                    next_state = STATE_L_F;\n                end\n            end\n            STATE_R_F: begin\n                if (ground) begin\n                    next_state = STATE_R_G;\n                end else begin\n                    next_state = STATE_R_F;\n                end\n            end\n            default: next_state = STATE_L_G;\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Moore output logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        walk_left  = 1'b0;\n        walk_right = 1'b0;\n        aaah       = 1'b0;\n\n        case (state) \n            STATE_L_G: walk_left  = 1'b1;\n            STATE_R_G: walk_right = 1'b1;\n            STATE_L_F: aaah       = 1'b1;\n            STATE_R_F: aaah       = 1'b1;\n        endcase\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
